    <section id="living-with" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living with diabetes</h2>
      <p>Managing a diabetic cat means building a daily routine — consistent mealtimes, insulin dosing, monitoring. It can feel overwhelming at first. Most owners become genuinely capable at it within weeks, and for many cats the daily management becomes unremarkable. Minou had both diabetes and CKD, which made every decision harder — the dietary needs for one condition can conflict with the other, and that tension doesn't always have a clean resolution.</p>
      <p>One thing that often goes undiscussed at diagnosis: some cats can achieve diabetic remission with aggressive early management. That possibility changes the conversation from "how do we manage this forever" to "what would it take to get off insulin." It is worth raising with your vet, especially in the first weeks after diagnosis.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>The framing that helps most:</strong> Diabetes management is less about chasing a perfect blood glucose number and more about avoiding the extremes — chronic highs that cause long-term damage, and lows that are immediately dangerous. Consistent, sustainable management beats perfect management that falls apart.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Ask about remission candidacy.</strong> Not every cat is a candidate, but every newly diagnosed cat deserves the question. What would it take, and how likely is it given your cat's situation?</li>
        <li><strong>Ask which insulin and why.</strong> Not all insulins are equal for cats. If you're not told the reasoning behind the choice, ask. There are options, and the choice matters.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about home glucose monitoring.</strong> Many owners can do this — it gives you better data and means you catch problems before the next appointment. If your vet hasn't raised it, ask whether it's appropriate for your cat.</li>
        <li><strong>Know the signs of a hypoglycaemic episode — and what to do.</strong> Low blood sugar is the most immediate danger. Make sure you have a clear protocol from your vet before you leave the clinic.</li>
        <li><strong>If your cat has other conditions, ask how they interact.</strong> CKD and diabetes together create genuine dietary conflicts. Name both conditions and ask your vet to address them together, not separately.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

